Nietzsche said Zarathustra. Most powerful arguments made concisely would be The Genealogy of Morals. Philosophers looking for overall intellectual coherence quickly might suggest The Will to Power (an organized compilation of unpublished notes). The small late books are great.

The tragedy (in the strict literary and religious sense) of The Anglo-Protestant Whig Tradition was imperialism. Classical liberalism made the English strong, their strength led to the conquest of a quarter of the world, and the empire led to globalist universalism, which swapped out their own moral and political tradition for another, tailored for everyone, and ultimately for themselves least of all.
